data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException` — it only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, modern .NET idiom would favor `Task`/`Parallel.ForEach` over raw threads:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

If you have **other** code that actually calls `Thread.Abort()` or catches `ThreadAbortException`, share it and I can provide specific migration guidance.
